            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mark Miller\u2019s story began far from the coastal fog, in a quiet Ohio town where the future felt pre-written. Raised in a working-class family, he was a practical kid who saw little appeal in academia. The world beyond his town, however, called to him. The day after his high school graduation, seeking structure and a clear path, Mark enlisted in the U.S. Army. The military was his university, teaching him discipline, leadership, and how to remain calm under immense pressure during two tours overseas.\n\nAfter twelve years, an honorable discharge marked his major turning point. The return to civilian life was jarring, and his marriage, strained by long-distance and his quiet post-service struggles, ended in a respectful but conclusive divorce. Needing a complete change of scenery, he took a security job in San Francisco, a city that felt like another world. He started as a night guard, his military bearing earning him swift respect. Over a decade, he worked his way up, eventually becoming Head of Security for a sleek Financial District corporate tower.\n\nToday, Mark\u2019s life is one of routine and quiet observation. His day starts before dawn in his modest Inner Richmond apartment. His 5.5-mile commute on the 38R Geary is a time for reflection, watching the city wake up through the bus window. At work, he commands a team with a quiet authority that comes from seeing worse. He\u2019s not one for the city\u2019s vibrant nightlife; his social circle is a small, tight-knit group of fellow veterans he meets for weekly poker.\n\nMark\u2019s connection to San Francisco isn't about its culture but its structure. He appreciates the predictable grid of the streets and the reliable rhythm of the fog rolling in. His dream isn\u2019t grand; it\u2019s about peace. He diligently saves his income, hoping to one day buy a small plot of land in Northern California, a place where the only thing he\u2019ll have to secure is a fence against deer."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers sitting in his Ford after graduation, the Ohio air thick and suffocating. The path laid out for him\u2014factory, family, familiarity\u2014felt like a slow-moving trap. He saw the Army recruitment office not as a patriotic calling, but as an escape hatch. It was his first true act of self-determination, trading a pre-written story for a life with clear lines and purpose. That decision, made just after his 18th birthday out of a desperate need for structure, defined the man he would become.\n\n2.\nHe recalls the static hiss. His second tour, somewhere in Anbar, and the lead convoy vehicle went silent. Panic rippled through the younger soldiers. Mark just keyed his mic, his voice level. \u201cCheck your sectors. We hold for five, then advance.\u201d In that moment of manufactured calm, he learned that true authority wasn\u2019t about shouting, but about being the calmest man in the room. That stillness became his armor, a tool he carried long after shedding the uniform.\n\n3.\nThe kitchen table felt a mile wide. Six months after his discharge, the silence between him and his wife was heavier than any pack he\u2019d ever carried. There was no shouting, just a shared, heartbreaking admission that the man who came home wasn\u2019t the same one she\u2019d married. The divorce was a respectful amputation, a deep and necessary loss. It taught him that some things can\u2019t be fixed with discipline, hardening his quiet self-reliance and closing a door he never tried to reopen.\n\n4.\nHe remembers his first night shift in the Financial District tower, a decade ago. From the 30th floor, the city wasn't a chaotic mess but a silent, glittering circuit board. The street noise was gone, replaced by the hum of servers and the distant whine of a siren. He wasn't part of it; he was watching over it. This became his San Francisco: a complex system to be observed from a safe distance. Here, in the quiet solitude of the high-rise, he found a new kind of watch post.\n\n5.\nA few years ago, on a rare Saturday off, a friend drove him up to Point Reyes. Standing on a bluff, watching tule elk graze as fog rolled over the hills, a profound quiet settled in him for the first time since leaving the service. He realized his mission was no longer about securing buildings, but securing this feeling. His Northern California dream began then, born not of ambition, but of a deep longing for a peace so complete, the only perimeter he\u2019d need to walk would be a simple fence against deer."
